        Which Cosmetic Renovations Add the Most Value Before Selling in Brisbane?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Not every pre-sale update is worth the cost. Here is which cosmetic renovations deliver the strongest return for Brisbane sellers, and which ones to leave well alone.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The question every vendor asks before listing is how much to spend getting the property ready, and where to spend it. The right answer is not the same for every property or every price point, but there is a consistent principle that applies almost universally: cosmetic updates that buyers notice immediately deliver the best return. Structural or hidden improvements rarely return their full cost at sale, because buyers cannot see them and will not pay a premium for something they have to take on faith.</p>

      <p>The goal of pre-sale preparation is not to renovate the property, it is to remove the reasons buyers use to discount their offer. Every cosmetic defect a buyer notices becomes a negotiating chip. Fresh paint, new carpet, and a clean, well-presented kitchen reduce the discounts buyers feel entitled to make and lift buyer confidence in the property's overall condition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Fresh paint: the highest-return cosmetic update</h2>
      <p>A fresh coat of paint throughout is the single most consistently effective pre-sale investment for Brisbane homes. It makes every room feel newer, cleaner, and better maintained than it is. Buyers walking through a freshly painted home feel a level of care and presentation that translates directly into confidence, and confidence translates into stronger offers.</p>

      <p>The colour choice matters. The goal is a neutral, contemporary palette, warm whites or soft greiges in the main living areas, that appeals to the broadest possible buyer pool rather than reflecting the current owner's taste. Polarising colour choices, whether bold features walls or dark tones throughout, will turn off a meaningful proportion of your potential buyers. Contemporary neutral is always safer.</p>

      <p>For an average-sized inner-east Brisbane home, professional painting typically costs between $5,000 and $15,000 depending on size, condition, and the number of rooms involved. The impact on buyer perception is rarely proportional to the cost. It is one of the few pre-sale investments where the return consistently exceeds the outlay in comparable sale analysis.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">New carpet in living areas and bedrooms</h2>
      <p>Worn, stained, or dated carpet is one of the most common reasons buyers discount their offers or walk away entirely. It is immediately visible, it signals poor maintenance, and buyers mentally add the cost of replacement to their offer calculation, often overestimating that cost. Replacing carpet before you list removes that discount trigger entirely.</p>

      <p>You do not need to install premium carpet to get the benefit. A mid-range product in a neutral tone, installed professionally throughout the main living areas and bedrooms, will look fresh, photograph well, and satisfy the vast majority of buyers. The cost is typically between $3,000 and $8,000 for a standard inner-east home, depending on floor area and the product chosen.</p>

      <p>If the property has original timber floors under the carpet, investigate that before deciding. In many inner-east Brisbane homes, polished or sanded timber boards under old carpet are a significantly more desirable outcome for buyers than new carpet, and the cost difference may be minimal. Your property manager or a flooring specialist can lift a corner of carpet in a cupboard to assess the condition of what is underneath.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Kitchen refresh: not a full renovation</h2>
      <p>A dated kitchen is one of the most common objections in buyer feedback. But a full kitchen renovation, with new cabinetry, benchtops, appliances, and layout changes, rarely returns its full cost when done in the weeks before selling. A targeted refresh almost always delivers better ROI.</p>

      <p>The highest-return kitchen updates are new cabinet handles and hardware, repainted or resprayed cabinet door fronts in a contemporary colour, updated tapware, a new splashback (either tile or a panel product), and a thorough deep clean including the rangehood filter and oven interior. Together, these changes can transform how a kitchen reads to a buyer for a cost of $3,000 to $8,000, compared to $40,000 or more for a full replacement. The kitchen will not look brand new, but it will not look tired either, and that is the goal.</p>

      <p>If appliances are visibly old or failing, replacing the cooktop and oven is worth considering. Buyers notice these and use them to negotiate. A new cooktop and oven costs $1,500 to $3,000 for good-quality products and sends a clear signal about the standard of maintenance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bathroom refresh: targeted improvements only</h2>
      <p>As with kitchens, full bathroom renovations are rarely worth the cost when done solely for sale. But a targeted refresh can significantly lift the presentation without major expenditure. The most effective bathroom updates are regrouting tiles (old or stained grout is the most common visual detractor in bathroom photos), replacing taps and showerhead with contemporary products, updating the vanity hardware, and resealing around the bath and shower.</p>

      <p>Professional regrouting for a standard bathroom costs around $400 to $800 and has a disproportionate visual impact, particularly in photography. New tapware costs $200 to $500 and makes the bathroom feel more contemporary than it is. Total cost for a comprehensive bathroom refresh of this kind is typically under $2,000, and the improvement in how the bathroom photographs and presents is significant.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Street appeal: the first impression problem</h2>
      <p>Buyers form their first impression of a property before they walk through the front door. Research consistently shows that street appeal drives a significant portion of the emotional response that shapes how much a buyer is willing to pay. A property that looks well-maintained from the street sends a signal about the entire house, and a property that looks tired does the opposite.</p>

      <p>The most effective street appeal improvements are low-cost but high-visibility. Pressure washing the driveway, paths, and any external tiled areas removes built-up grime and instantly lifts the appearance. Fresh mulch in garden beds, a tidy lawn, and pruned hedges cost very little and take a day of effort. Painting the front fence if it is tired or peeling, and replacing front door hardware such as the handle, knocker, and house numbers, are small investments that disproportionately improve how the property reads to a buyer arriving for an inspection.</p>

      <p>If the external paintwork is significantly faded or peeling, that needs to be addressed. Buyers notice it, it photographs poorly, and it suggests the property has not been cared for. External painting is a larger investment but one that consistently pays back in Brisbane's inner-east market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to spend money on before selling</h2>
      <p>Knowing what to leave alone is as important as knowing what to fix. Full kitchen or bathroom renovations almost never return their full cost in a pre-sale context. Adding a pool or outdoor structure adds significant cost and extends your timeline without delivering reliable return at sale. Structural repairs, unless the issue is visible and significant (a cracked foundation, a failing roof), are often better disclosed than fixed, since the cost of proper rectification often exceeds what buyers discount for the issue.</p>

      <p>Personalised improvements that narrow your buyer pool, custom colours, unusual finishes, or highly specific design choices, should be avoided entirely. The goal is to appeal to the broadest possible group of buyers, not to reflect your personal taste. What you love about the property may be exactly what a buyer needs to change before they can see themselves living there.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to prioritise with a limited budget</h2>
      <p>If your budget for pre-sale preparation is limited, apply it in this order. Start with what buyers see first: street appeal and the entry. Then address the most obvious negatives, the worn carpet, the stained grout, the dated kitchen handles. Fresh paint is almost always worth doing if the budget allows it. Leave structural and hidden items alone unless they are actively failing.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be able to walk through the property with you and give you a specific list of what to address and what to leave. A good agent has seen enough comparable sales in the area to know which defects buyers actually discount for and which ones they overlook. That knowledge is valuable, and you should use it to focus your preparation budget where it will actually move the needle on your result.</p>

